hor's analysis of original audio recordings of the speech events (several of which will be available on a companion website) improves our understanding of the spoken, performative dimension of public speeches.While emphasizing the social constructedness of discourse, experience, and identity, Boos does not neglect the pragmatic conditions of aesthetic and intellectual production-most notably, the felt need to respond to the breach in tradition caused by the Holocaust. The book thereby illuminates the process by which a set of writers and intellectuals, instead of trying to mend what they perceived as a radical break in historical continuity or corroborating the myth of a "new beginning," searched for ways to make this historical rupture rhetorically and semantically discernible and literally audible.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionzGermany (West). 0aSpeeches, addresses, etc., GermanxHistory and criticism. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9780801471957zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801471957zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801471957.jpg  a978-3-11-060674-4 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA